# EscapeZoom: Modern WP–Laravel Hybrid Architecture

## Zero-Plugin Policy
- No WordPress plugins for business features. Composer for backend, NPM for frontend.
- Only agreed infra/dev plugins allowed (e.g. tooling, not business logic).

## Framework & Packages
- **Backend:** Eloquent for custom data; Illuminate Validation for forms; Guzzle for HTTP; standard packages for Iranian gateways.
- **Frontend:** Agreed stack (Embla, GSAP, Alpine, etc.) per project rules; no ad-hoc libraries.

## Directory Standards (mu-plugins/escapezoom-core)
- `src/Models` — thin; persistence only.
- `src/Services` — all heavy business logic.
- `src/Http` or `src/Controllers` — thin; delegate to services only.
- `src/Integration` — third-party API clients and adapters.
- `database/migrations` — schema changes.
- `templates/` or agreed frontend folder for server-rendered output.

## Service Layer
- Complex logic lives in Services. Use a service container / DI; classes must not `new` each other.
- Hooks and controllers call services only; no business logic in controllers or hook callbacks.

## Frontend
- **Build:** Vite as the build tool. Tailwind utility-first. Stencil for Web Components where specified; Alpine for local state where specified.
- **Workflow:** Run build after any change to `template/` or frontend assets so compiled output is up to date.

## Don’t Reinvent the Wheel
- Use Composer/NPM packages for validation, PDF, QR, HTTP, etc., per project rules (e.g. rule 02). Prefer off-the-shelf over custom implementations.
